Fc-OPG PK/PD in healthy post-menopausal women

Metrum Research Group

1 Packages

library(mrgsolve)
library(tidyverse)
library(magrittr)
library(furrr)

1.1 Question

  • What is the median change from baseline 14 days after 3 mg/kg SC dose?
  • What is the probability that median CFB is greater than 40%?

For most of our examples, we are taking output directly from a NONMEM run. This example is a little different: We have changed the column names from THETA1, THETA2 etc … to TVCL, TVVC etc …

head(post)

inventory(mod,post)
post <- mutate(post, TVVP1 = TVP1, TVVP2 = TVP2)

When working with results out of NONMEM, it is common to get the THETA , OMEGA and SIGMA estimates all in a single row in a data frame.

In order to get the information for OMEGA and SIGMA in to the problem, we need to go into this data and form matrices.

There are two specialized functions to help with this:

  • as_bmat when the data is in block format
  • as_dmat when the data is in diagonal format
omegas <- as_bmat(post,"OMEGA")
sigmas <- as_bmat(post,"SIGMA")

We will get the observation design for the simulation through a tgrid object

des <- tgrid(end=-1,add=c(0,24*14))

. start:  0  end:    -1  delta:  1  offset: 0  min:    0   max:    336

When we do replicate simulation, it almost always pays off to construct a function that will carry out one replicate.

Arguments to the function are

  • i the current simulation replicate
  • data the dosing data set
  • des the observation design
sim <- function(i,data,des) {
  
  mod <- 
    mod %>%
    param(slice(post,i)) %>%
    omat(omegas[[i]]) %>% 
    smat(sigmas[[i]])
  
  mod %>%
    Req(PDDV) %>%
    mrgsim(data=data,tgrid=des,obsonly=TRUE) %>% 
    mutate(irep=i) %>% 
    mutate(TVIC50=mod$TVIC50, TVQ1=mod$TVQ1, TVVMAX=mod$TVVMAX)
}

Also note

  • We update param with ith row from post
  • We update OMEGA and SIGMA from the ith position in the appropriate list of matrices
  • We will capture the current

It is easy to test the function. The 10th replicate will look like this

sim(10,sc3,des)

Summarise

  • First, get the baseline NTX
  • Then calculate percent CFB
sum <- 
  out %>%
  group_by(ID,irep) %>%
  mutate(BASE = first(PDDV), dDV = 100*(PDDV-BASE)/BASE) %>%
  ungroup

Filter down to week 2

sum <- sum %>% filter(time==336 & BASE >= 0)

Now, get the median

summ <- 
  sum %>%
  filter(time==336) %>%
  group_by(irep) %>%
  summarise(med = median(dDV))

3.1 From the abstract

Subsequent clinical trial simulations demonstrated that a single 3.0-mg/kg SC dose of Fc-OPG would be expected to produce, at 14 days post-dose, a median NTX percentage change from baseline of −45% (with a 95% prediction interval ranging from −34% to −60%)."

ans <- signif(quantile(summ$med, c(0.5,0.025,0.975)),3)
